    "rationale": "This example demonstrates the Pfitzner-Moffatt oxidation of a secondary alcohol (1-cyclohexylethanol) to the corresponding ketone (acetylcyclohexane). The substrate is simple, acyclic on the reactive center but contains a common cycloalkane, making it specific enough to avoid being a generic seed. The reaction is a classic application of this named reaction, using DMSO activated by a carbodiimide (DCC) in the presence of a mild acid catalyst.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "The substrate is a non-trivial secondary alcohol, 1-cyclohexylethanol. This specific structure is chosen to be distinct from overly simple examples like propan-2-ol or cyclohexanol, and also distinct from complex natural product fragments, thus reducing the likelihood of collision with generic oxidation seeds or highly specific literature examples.",
    "reagents_text": "Dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO), Dicyclohexylcarbodiimide (DCC), Pyridinium trifluoroacetate",
    "conditions_text": "Room temperature, Dichloromethane (DCM) or Benzene as solvent"
  }
}
